{0 ocaml-pdb}

An OCaml library for reading and writing Microsoft PDB (Program
Database) files and the CodeView debugging records they contain.

A PDB is the file a Windows compiler writes alongside an executable so
that a debugger can recover source-level information at runtime. Answering
questions like:

- which machine address corresponds to which source line;
- what the local variables and parameters look like;
- what the types of those variables are;
- how to unwind the stack at any point in a function.

On Linux/macOS this information lives inside the executable in DWARF
sections. On Windows it lives in a separate [.pdb] file with its own
on-disk format.

{1 Where to start}

If you are not already familiar with the PDB / CodeView formats, read
the {{!page-concepts}concepts guide} first. It walks through what is
inside a PDB file, why the data is split across many "streams", and how
the streams reference each other, with no Windows background assumed.

If you already know the format and just want to use the library, jump
straight to {!Pdb.Pdb_builder} (high-level write) or {!Pdb.Msf}
(low-level read of the on-disk container).

{1 Library}

The entry point is the {!Pdb} module, which re-exports every
component module:

{!modules:Pdb}

